---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import ExploreTopics from "../components/ExploreTopics.astro";
import palaeolithicDogMap from "../assets/images/palaeolithic-dog-map.avif";
---

<BaseLayout title="ANT 104 - Coevolution Research">
  <header
    class="rela ive overflow-hidden bg-gradient-to-br from-paper via-white to-paper py-6 md:py-8"
  >
    <div
      class="pointer-events-none absolute top-0 left-0 w-64 h-64 bg-sage/5 rounded-full -translate-x-1/2 -translate-y-1/2"
    >
    </div>
    <div
      class="pointer-events-none absolute bottom-0 right-0 w-96 h-96 bg-terracotta/5 rounded-full translate-x-1/2 translate-y-1/2"
    >
    </div>
    <div class="relative z-10 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 text-center">
      <span
        class="inline-block px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-terracotta bg-terracotta/10 rounded-full mb-2"
        >ANT 104 · Coevolution</span
      >
      <h1 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-ink mb-2 leading-tight">
        Coevolution of Humans and Dogs: From Hunting and Gathering to Farming
      </h1>
    </div>
  </header>
  <section
    class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-2 text-xs sm:text-sm text-muted"
    aria-label="Assignment details"
  >
    <div
      class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-x-8 gap-y-0 mx-auto max-w-fit text-center"
    >
      <p class="m-0"><strong>Name:</strong> Hammy Siddiqui</p>
      <p class="m-0"><strong>Date:</strong> June 9, 2026</p>
      <p class="m-0"><strong>Class:</strong> ANT 104 - Intro to Bio Anthro</p>
      <p class="m-0"><strong>Professor:</strong> Dr. Alexandra Sumner</p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <main class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-3">
    <div class="prose-custom space-y-6 text-ink/85 leading-relaxed">
      <p class="mt-2">
        I chose this topic because I've always known about and been disheartened
        by the cruel dog breeding humans have done. I know that since the
        Victorian era, humans have been selectively breeding dogs not for
        functionality or ability, but for competitions, appearance, and luxury.
        Many of these dogs have eventually developed severe mobility and
        breathing issues, like pugs. From recent knowledge I learned from social
        media, dachshunds were bred before the Victorian era for a specific and
        functional reason. Their long bodies and small statures were selectively
        bred to have the perfect shape to hunt badgers in their own tunnels.
        Learning this and reading the topic list, I immediately thought of how
        the era-defining change from hunting to farming affected dogs and
        humans. I had a couple of questions leading the start of my research:
      </p>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink mt-8 mb-4">
        Research Questions
      </h2>
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6 space-y-2 text-ink/85">
        <li>When did humans start domesticating dogs?</li>
        <li>Why did humans start domesticating dogs?</li>
        <li>What was the relationship between dogs and humans?</li>
        <li>
          Did the switch from hunting and gathering to farming affect the way
          humans selectively bred dogs in any biological ways?
        </li>
      </ul>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink mt-8 mb-4">
        Research Findings
      </h2>
      <p class="mb-4">Quotes researchers said and agreed on:</p>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-ink/85">
        <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-terracotta pl-4 my-4 italic text-ink/70">
          <p class="mb-2">
            "All zooarchaeologists support the contention that dogs were not only
            the first domestic animal, but that the appearance of dogs
            significantly predates the origins of domestic plants and early
            agriculture"
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm">(Larson 1)</p>
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-terracotta pl-4 my-4 italic text-ink/70">
          <p class="mb-2">
            "Dogs were the first domestic animal, but little is known about their
            population history and to what extent it was linked to humans. We
            sequenced 27 ancient dog genomes and found that all dogs share a
            common ancestry distinct from present-day wolves"
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm">(Bergström 557)</p>
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-terracotta pl-4 my-4 italic text-ink/70">
          <p class="mb-2">
            "Dogs were the only domestic species present in both Europe and the
            Near East prior to the Neolithic"
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm">(Ollivier 1)</p>
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-terracotta pl-4 my-4 italic text-ink/70">
          <p class="mb-2">
            "Understanding when and where our relationship with dogs began is
            crucial to comprehending the transition of humans from
            hunter-gatherers to farmers"
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm">(Larson 1)</p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      <figure class="mt-12">
        <Image
          src={palaeolithicDogMap}
          alt="Map showing sites where domesticated dogs are unearthed across western Eurasia"
          class="max-w-full h-auto rounded-lg shadow-sm mx-auto"
        />
        <figcaption
          class="text-xs text-muted text-center mt-3 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mx-auto"
        >
          Sites where domesticated dogs are unearthed. Dog remains excavated at
          Pinarbaşi in Türkiye date to about 15,800 years ago; at Gough's Cave
          in the UK to about 14,300 years ago; and at Kesslerloch in Switzerland
          to about 14,200 years ago. DNA analysis confirms that domesticated
          dogs are widespread across western Eurasia in the Paleolithic, before
          the introduction of agriculture./Courtesy of Nature.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
    <ExploreTopics current="home" />
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
